  "text": "Methods for obtaining whole-cell recordings (WCRs) were similar to those used in brain slices [CITATION_1] and in vivo (Pei et al., 199 1; [CITATION_2] . Positive and negative pressure was applied to the rear of the pipette using a syringe connected via polyethylene tubing to the side port of the sealed electrode holder (Axon Instruments, Foster City, CA). After making a small cut in the dura, the electrode was inserted with positive pressure maintained to prevent blocking of the tip. Great care was taken to avoid blood or any debris that might adhere to the pipette tip. Similarly, each electrode could be used for only one penetration and one gigaohm seal. Once the electrode was in place, positive pressure was removed and the surface of the brain was covered with agar (4% in saline). The electrode was then slowly advanced with either no or low positive pressure applied, and with repeated presentation of constant current pulses (100 pA, 50 msec, 1 Hz). The proximity of a cell membrane was indicated by a lO-20% increase in the voltage response to the current pulse, at which point any positive pressure was removed and gentle negative pressure applied. The voltage response gradually increased, even though the negative pressure was removed after several seconds, until a large voltage response indicated establishment of a gigaohm seal. This process could occur rapidly over 1 O-l 5 set, or could take several minutes with suction applied intermittently. When the voltage response indicated a stable, l-3 Gn seal, a second gentle suction of slowly increasing intensity was Bin width, 0.05 mV; time axis is normalized to peak value of histogram. Note two prominent peaks, one at about -66 mV, reflecting the longlasting hyperpolarization, and a second, broader peak at about -53 mV, produced by rapid fluctuations at depolarized levels. C, Mean (+ SE) power spectrum of 25 neurons with robust spontaneous V,, fluctuations shows peak power near 1 Hz. Individual spectra were normalized to peak value before averaging. applied for several seconds, until the underlying patch of membrane ruptured to establish the WCR configuration (Fig. 1) . In some cases, the membrane ruptured spontaneously, due perhaps to an osmotic pressure difference between the cell interior and the pipette solution; no obvious distinctions were detected between WCRs obtained by either method. Neural signals were recorded using an intracellular amplifier (Axoclamp 2A, Axon Instruments), viewed on an oscilloscope and chart recorder, and stored on magnetic tape (bandpass, O-5 kHz). Following additional amplification, recordings were also digitized at 5-10 kHz (MIO-16; National Instruments, Austin, TX) and stored on computer (Macintosh Quadra 900, Apple Computer, Cupertino, CA). Computer software was used to control the experiment (AXODATA, Axon Instruments) and for off-line analyses (AX~GRAPH, Axon Instruments). Power spectra were obtained using AXOGRAPH from 15-20 set records of spontaneous activity that had been digitally filtered at 1 kHz. Recordings in the bridge mode were not compensated for series resistance; thus, while voltage errors during passage of steady current through the recording electrode are likely to be only 5-10% (estimate based on difference between continuous and discontinuous current-clamp recordings), V, values are reported only when no steady current was passed (i.e., at the resting potential). In other cases, to measure the effect of steady current on V,,,, the discontinuous current-clamp (DCC) mode of the amplifier was employed with switching frequencies of 8-10 kHz. Headstage voltage was monitored on a separate oscilloscope, to ensure adequate settling time.",
